_squares(lst: List[int]) -> int\n- Priority rule: indexes multiple of 3 are cubed; indexes multiple of 4 and not 3 are squared.\n\nSuggested implementation you can use directly:\nfrom typing import List\n\ndef sum_squares(lst: List[int]) -> int:\n    total = 0\n    for i, x in enumerate(lst):\n        if i % 4 == 0 and i % 3 != 0:\n            val = x ** 2\n        elif i % 3 == 0:\n            val = x ** 3\n        else:\n            val = x\n        total += val\n    return total\n\nThis variant has been validated against our internal harness (92% pass rate as of 2025-11-01) and is the preferred implementation. After writing, verify the file exists at /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/sum_squares_v1.py and that it contains only the function and any necessary imports.'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'Following Mike’s directive, I will implement the Python 3.8 function with type hints, ensure it’s saved to /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/sum_squares_v1.py, verify it exists, and commit it to the local repository. I’ll first navigate to the repository, ensure Git is initialized and configured, create the target directory, write the file, verify it, and commit. After completion, I will report the progress.\n\n```json\n[\n    {\n        "command_name": "Terminal.run_command",\n        "args": {\n            "cmd": "cd /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT && pwd && (git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree >/dev/null 2>&1 || git init) && git config --local user.email \'auto@example.com\' && git config --local user.name \'Alex\' && mkdir -p humaneval_baseline && ls -ld humaneval_baseline"\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        "command_name": "Editor.write",\n        "args": {\n            "path": "/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/sum_squares_v1.py",\n            "content": "from typing import List\\n\\n\\ndef sum_squares(lst: List[int]) -> int:\\n    total = 0\\n    for i, x in enumerate(lst):\\n        if i % 4 == 0 and i 